<HTML>
<HEAD><title>Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act -- ATR</title></head>
<BODY Bgcolor=#FFFFFF><CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER>
<BOLD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>
Why We Need the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act
</FONT><ADDRESS>By Rep. Dick Armey</ADDRESS>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=30%></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="gstil.gif" ALT=DICK ARMEY>


	<FONT SIZE=+2>G</Font>overnment spends, taxes, and regulates too much.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>O</Font>f all the crises facing America, this one is paramount.  Many other major national problems flow from this fact or are greatly compounded because of it.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>S</Font>tagnant wages and stifled job growth, urban violence and poverty, and soaring health care and education costs are all closely related to or influenced by the unchecked expansion of the public sector.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>	O</Font>n a deeper level, the growth of government is our most critical problem because it so greatly affects the definition of what it means to be an American.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>O</Font>ur government has expanded, it has assumed duties that previously belonged to families and communities, leaving those institutions weaker and government stronger.  A distinct governing class emerged with a taste for power and an appetite for more.  Often relying upon guile, some leaders of this class worked to extend government's intrusive power far beyond what earlier American generations would have tolerated.  Today, we find ourselves staggering under an immense government burden, serving an entrenched elite that in many ways presumes to be wiser and nobler than the rest of us.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>B</Font>asic American rights should include freedom from unfair demands of distant rulers and the right to use our own efforts to build a better future for our children.  Clearly these rights are being undermined by excessively big government and something is very wrong.  Unrestrained growth of government is a threat to the American Dream.  Consider what runaway governmental power  means to the aspirations of a typical American family.<P>
	"John and Marie Hargas" of Westerville, Ohio, work hard, make mortgage payments, save for their children's college tuition, and give to their church and charities.  Their primary ambition is to make life better for themselves and their two small children.<P>
But each year as April 15 approaches, they typically spend eleven hours filling out IRS forms.  When they're through, they discover that more than a quarter of their income has fled to government bureaucrats five hundred miles away in Washington, D.C.  That amount includes 10.5 percent in direct income taxes, and a whopping 15.5 percent in FICA payroll taxes for payments to Social Security.  The government takes Hargas' earnings from their employers before the Hargases ever see it.  <FONT SIZE=+1>Their state and local taxes take 12.6 percent of their income.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>I</Font>n all, more than 40 percent of the Hargases earnings support government at all levels.  <Address>That is more than they spend on food, clothing and shelter combined.</Address>  In effect, all the work they do from January 1 to May 6 each year is for government.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>E</Font>very American is entitled to ask these fundamental questions: "Does government really have to cost this much?  Are we really getting our money's worth?  Is this a fair cost for the value we receive from government?"<P>
 <FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>n addition to direct taxes, there is a hidden cost of government that is much more difficult to measure.  That immense additional cost of government is caused by regulations which increase the price of every product and service we buy from peanut butter to cars.<P>
  <FONT SIZE=+2>R</Font>egulations add at least $580 billion in annual costs to U.S. consumers.  That means the Hargases must spend another large part of their income bearing their share of the rule-writers' burden.  According to <BOLD>Americans for Tax Reform</BOLD>, Americans actually labor until <A HREF="/atr/cogdpak.html">July 9</A> before they stop working for the government's ends and begin working for their own.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</Font>he Hargases think of themselves as free Americans living in a fair society.  But how free are they really?	In America's peacetime history, never before has government had so much power over family life.<P>
  <FONT SIZE=+2>T</Font>he U.S. public sector budget is larger than the gross domestic product of any country in the world except for Japan and the U.S. itself.  Since 1950, per capita federal spending has tripled.  Federal spending alone has risen from 16 percent of our 1950 economy to 23 percent in 1991.  By the year 2000, spending could be 27 percent of GNP and reach  31 percent by 2010 unless something is done to reverse the trend. <P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>B</Font>ased on current projections, the <BOLD>annual federal budget
</BOLD> will reach nearly 
<UL><L1><BOLD>$1.9 trillion by the year 2000,</BOLD> <L1>
<BOLD>$2.7 trillion in 2010</BOLD> <L1><BOLD>$4 trillion by the year 2020.</UL><BOLD>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>	E</Font>ach new dollar government spends and each increase in the size of the government relative to the economy represents an encroachment on the freedom of individual taxpayers.  For people like John and Marie Hargas, that means an ever larger portion of their income will be taken from them.  They will have less control over their lives as the government class, dominated by political professionals, becomes more powerful.  Both the Hargas family and the nation will become poorer as freedom is taken away.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A</Font>mericans face a fundamental choice:  Should the government become ever larger as freedom diminishes--or should we take dramatic action now to halt the growth of government and restore greater freedom to our country?<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</Font>he "Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act"
 is a way of saying "Enough is Enough."	It is a comprehensive assault on Big Government, designed to halt its growth, expose its true cost, and limit its influence on the lives of free Americans.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>I</Font>t does this by radically reordering the three major activities of the federal government: taxing, spending, and regulating.
<hr noshade=40%><br>
 The Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act proposes:<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2><BOLD>A Flat Tax.</BOLD></FONT>  Scraps the current tax code and replaces it with a simple and neutral tax code based on 17 percent flat tax on all income.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>Rigid Spending Caps.</BOLD></FONT>   Places unbreachable spending caps on all forms of federal spending to ensure that the federal government will never grow larger in real terms than it is today.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>Program Sunsets</BOLD></FONT>.  Forces the true reinvention of government by ending the authorization of  virtually all existing federal spending programs. <P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>Open Government</BOLD></FONT>.  Exposes the hidden cost of government, ending income tax withholding and 	requiring the government for  the first time to calculate the cost of regulations.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>Regulatory Relief</BOLD></FONT>.  Treats regulations much like federal spending, requiring annual calculation of  the total costs to the nation of complying with federal regulations, and providing means for limiting this burden.<P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>Property Rights Protection.</BOLD></FONT>  Secures property rights by requiring the government to compensate landowners whenever federal regulations significantly reduce the value of their property.  <P>
	<FONT SIZE=+2>Rational Risk Assessment</BOLD></FONT>.  Requires the government to determine the cost, benefits, and risks of 	all new regulations before it imposes new costs on the economy.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>	The excessive growth of government is the central problem of our time. We need the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act to contain that growth once and for all. </font><P>

	Rep. Dick Armey (R-Texas) is Majority Leader of the U.S. House of Representatives.
<HR noshade=100%>
 <P> 
</FONT><ADDRESS><A HREF="MAILTO:atr@townhall.com">Americans for Tax Reform</A><FONT SIZE=3><BOLD> 
<BR>
1320 18th Street NW Suite 200<BR>
Washington, DC 20036<BR></ADDRESS>
<P>
