</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
 
<HEAD>
<title>FLAT TAX: THE ANSWER TO AMERICA'S TAX PROBLEMS -- ATR</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="yuck.gif"><B><FONT SIZE=+4>       F</FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>lat </FONT><FONT SIZE=+4>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>ax:</FONT></B><P>

<B><IMG SRC="ball_blue.gif"><FONT SIZE=+2>THE ANSWER TO AMERICA'S TAX PROBLEMS</B></FONT><IMG SRC="ball_blue.gif"></CENTER><br>by Grover G. Norquist<P>

<HR>

Their is a new name for tax relief:  "The Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act" introduced by Texas Congressman and House Majority Leader Dick Armey.  Most people call it "the flat tax" for short.<P>

Armey would vaporize the entire federal income tax code and replace it with a simple plan.  Individual taxpayers would add up all their income form wages, salaries, or pension.  Then they would subtract a generous personnel allowance -- $13,100 for a single person, $17,200 for a single head of household, or $26,200 for a married couple, plus $5300 for each dependent.  Then they pay a flat 17 percent on what's left.<P>

Thus, a family of four would pay no income tax on income under $36,000.  A family of six -- two parents, four children -- would pay no tax on income under $47,400.<P>

The small business owner would add up total receipts less cash wages and the cost of goods, services, and supplies used in the business, as well as all capital equipment.  Then he or she pays a flat 17 percent on the remainder.  Translation: the business owner pays only a pure tax on business profits as generally conceived, before tax accountants, lobbyists, lawyers, and politicians start messing things up.<P>

The flat tax permits no credits, deductions, exceptions, or loopholes.  There is nothing that allows elected officials a foothold in the system.  Big business plays by exactly the same rules small business does.  Big companies get no special breaks and cannot easily lobby for them.  Business and individuals alike pay taxes only for themselves; they do not become veritable arms of the IRS collecting for other peoples as they do in a sales tax system.<P>

Best of all, there are no depreciation schedules.  Business owners get immediate expensing for all capital purchases.  There is also no inheritance tax.  Your heirs will pay tax on the income your business or farm generates when you leave it to them.  Maintenance of family business or family farms becomes far easier.  The government gets no information about what your financial holdings are.<P>

Armey modeled his proposal on a 1981 plan by Stanford Economists Robert Hall and Alvin Rabushka, which many consider the simplest and most elegant tax system ever devised.  The beauty of the flat tax is that it taxes all income, just once, visibly, with no intermediary between government and taxpayer, in a way that allows taxpayers to unite against profligate government.<P>

In keeping with its inherent libertarianism, the flat tax is also perfectly neutral with respect to all economic decisions.  There is no penalty against saving, to be sure, and no double or triple taxation of corporate income.  But on the other hand, there is no bias against saving either.  You can save or consume, spend now or spend later, invest your money wisely or waste it if you will.  You can buy foreign goods and luxury items or the cheapest domestic products, even goods from industries with more or less political protection.  There is no way a government planner can encourage you to spend money one wary or the other with differential taxation.  Your purchasing decisions just don't matter.  The tax in all cases is exactly the same.<P>

Compare the falt tax to our present system, which favors consumption over investment, short term over long term horizons, debt over equity, and service over manufacturing industry.  Many in big business and the world of policy wonkery say we should tax consumption more to level the playing field.  Armey says no.  We should tax everything, across the board, less.<P>

Armey builds on the fundamental insight that taxes need reforming because taxes are too high and government spends too much.  The current U.S. tax code is a crazy hodge-podge of conflicting features for a single reason:  once politicians get hold of a tax, they just can't let go.  As a result, minor fixes that could make the current tax code much less a barrier to long term growth just don't get made.  Politicians won't pay for tax simplification and lower marginal rates even if it means much better economic performance over time.  They would much rather have a little money to buy some nice fresh pork right now.<P>

This why we have a capital gains tax.  Capital gains as now administered is a relatively small levy which costs the economy disastrously in terms of lost economic growth.  There is no economic justifications whatever for the tax, but at least we could lessen its impact by adjusting asset bases for inflation, as the Contract with  

 


 












</DOC>
