<HEAD>

<TITLE>Competitive Markets in Electric Energy -- PFF</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Rick F. O'Donnell">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Michael Sparks">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<map name="wst">
<area shape="rect" coords="0,0,92,20" href="#works">
<area shape="rect" coords="93,0,193,20" href="#speeches">
<area shape="rect" coords="194,0,318,20" href="#testimonies"></map>

<ul><blockquote>

<a href="welcome.html"><img src="bi.gif" align="right" border="0" alt="PFF"></a>
<center>
<a href="wst.map"><img src="wst.gif" border="0" USEMAP="#wst" ISMAP></a>
<img src="nrghead.gif" alt="Competitive Markets in Electric Energy">
</center>
<br><br><P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="20%">Why should I care about this, you ask?  Because the computer you
are using right now is consuming power that costs you money on
your electricity bill every month - costs that have the potential
to be reduced significantly with sound reform.  Electric energy
is huge; the United States is home to nearly 1/3 of the installed
electric generating capacity in the world.
<P>
Why does the Federal government own some of it?  And why is it
regulated in a way to make a Soviet bureaucrat proud?  Should you - and
could you - choose the source of your power just like you choose
your long-distance company?  The Japanese are building tons of
it, the French have a flourishing industry in it, but in America
the nuclear energy industry is dying.<h4><a href="nrglink.html">Why?</a></h4>
<td valign="top">
<br><img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="pri21.html"><b>Lights out on Federal Power</a></b> by Congressman John Shadegg and Dr. Michael Block
<br><img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="pop-14.html"><b>Power to the People</a></b> by Congressman John Shadegg and Michael Block
<br><img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="arizona.html"><b>Report from the Experimental Competition Lab</a></b> in Arizona
<br><img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="congtest/ct0895-1.html"><b>Testimony on PUHCA</a></b> by Tom Lenard
<br><img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="/pff/puhca/610puhca.html"><b>The Benefits of Repealing PUHCA</a></b> by Thomas M. Lenard, R. Richard Geddes, R. Richard Geddes.
</tr></table>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<P><br><P>
<center>
<P>
