          significantly increase growth.
</blockquote><p>
Manvel, Allen D. 1982.  "The Puzzling Washington Post."
     <i>Tax Notes</i> (May 17), pp. 572-574.
<blockquote>
          Takes issue with a <i>Washington Post</i> editorial on April
          15, 1982 which supported a flat-rate tax.  (The
          editorial said "The ideal income tax would be a flat
          percentage on all income above an arbitrary threshold
          of, say, $10,000 a year.")
</blockquote><p>
McCaleb, Thomas S. 1985.  "Public Choice Perspectives on the Flat
     Tax Follies."  <i>Cato Journal</i>, vol. 5, no. 2 (Fall), pp. 613-
624.
<blockquote>
          Opposes flat-rate tax on public choice grounds.  See
          also McKenzie (1982).
</blockquote><p>
McCulloch, John R. 1852.  <i>A Treatise on the Principles and
     Practical Influence of Taxation and the Funding System</i>. 
     London: Longman, Brown, Green & Longmans, p. 141.
<blockquote>
          "The moment you abandon, the framing of such taxes, the
          cardinal principle of exacting from all individuals the
          same proportion of their income or of their property,
          you are at sea without rudder or compass, and there is
          no amount of injustice and folly you may not commit."
</blockquote><p>
McIntyre, Michael. 1983.  "Neither Low Nor Simple Nor Fair."  <i>The
     New Republic</i> (July 11), pp. 35-37.
<blockquote>
          Reviews Hall and Rabushka (1983).  Believes that their
          proposal is unfair.
</blockquote><p>
McIntyre, Robert S. 1982.  "Flat-Rate Talk."  <i>The New Republic</i> (July 19 & 26), pp. 20-22.
<blockquote>
          Although opposed to a flat-rate, the author, who is
          head of Citizens for Tax Justice, believes that the
          discussion of a flat-rate usefully draws attention to
          unnecessary loopholes in the tax code.
</blockquote><p>
McIntyre, Robert S. 1995a. "The Flat Taxers' Flat Deceptions." <i>The American Prospect</i> (Summer), pp. 93-95.
