O'Neill, Harry, and Kenneth Schwartz. 1982.  "Flat Tax Facts."  <i>Public Opinion</i> (October/November), pp. 44-46.
<blockquote>
          Reports on a public opinion survey on flat rate tax. 
          Indicates that 45% favor flat-rate, 41% favor
          progressive tax.  However, 20% to 30% of flat-rate
          supporters would reject it if forced to give-up
          particular deductions.
</blockquote><p>
<a name="P"></a>P-R<p>
<a href="#quick">Back to QuickLinks</a><p>

Paul, Ron. 1982.  "The Flatter the Better?"  <i>Inquiry</i> (September),
     pp. 29-33.
<blockquote>
          Prominent libertarian (he was the Libertarian Party's
          presidential candidate in 1984) strongly favors a flat-
rate tax because "it would spread the burden of paying
          for government more evenly, foreclosing once and for
          all the illusion that the burden can be placed on the
          shoulders of the rich.  By shifting the tax burden
          toward the political center, any flat-rate tax would
          increase pressure for less government taxing and
          spending."  Contrast with Rothbard.
</blockquote><p>
Payne, James L. 1993.  <i>Costly Returns: The Burdens of the U.S. Tax System</i>.  San Francisco: ICS Press.
<blockquote>
          Estimates the compliance cost of the federal tax system
          at 65% of revenue collected.  Contrast with Blumenthal
          and Slemrod (1992) and Slemrod and Sorum (1984).
</blockquote><p>
Pechman, Joseph A., and Michael J. Boskin. 1982.  "Flat Rate Taxes: Two Views."  <i>Tax Notes</i> (August 16), pp. 651-653.
<blockquote>
          A tax expert from the Brookings Institution and a
          professor of economics at Stanford debate the
          desirability of a flat-rate tax.  Pechman is against it
          and Boskin is for it.
</blockquote><p>
Pechman, Joseph A., and John Karl Scholz. 1982.  "Comprehensive Income Taxation and Rate Reduction."  <i>Tax Notes</i> (October
     11), pp. 83-93.
