<html>
<head>
<title>Adjunct Fellows -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="../notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote><ul>
<a href="/pff"><img src="../pffdoc.gif" border="0" align="right"></a>
<map name="people">
<area shape="rect" coords="0,0,70,20" href="../mission.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="71,0,144,20" href="director.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="145,0,249,20" href="sfellow.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="251,0,364,20" href="afellow.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="365,0,415,20" href="staff.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="417,0,459,20" href="/pff"> 
</map>

<center><a href="people.map"><img src="i-people.gif" border="0" align="top" ISMAP USEMAP="#people"></a>
<h1>Adjunct Fellows</h1></center>
<p>

<dt><b><a name="Connor">Daryl Connor</a></b>
<ul>Daryl Connor educates and advises executives
around the world in the field of change-management.  He is the founder
and chief executive officer of ODR, Inc., a research and development
firm dedicated to the study of change-management.  He has published
a book, <i>Managing at the Speed of Change,</i> and more than 80
journal and magazine articles, monographs and book chapters.</ul>

<p>

<dt><b><a name="Dale">Edwin Dale, Jr.<a></b>

<ul>From 1955 to 1976, Dale was an economic correspondent with the
Washington and Paris Bureaus of The <a href="http://nytsyn.com/"><i>New York Times.</i></a> In 1977, he joined the staff
of the Subcommittee on Economic Stabilization of the House Banking Committee.
During the Reagan administration, Dale was the Assistant Director for Public
Affairs as well as spokesman under Directors David Stockman and James Miller at
the <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/White_House/EOP/html/other/OMB.html">Office of Management and Budget</a>. In late 1987, he became Counselor to
Secretary of Commerce William Verity. From there, after the election of President
Bush, Dale returned to OMB, serving as Counselor and Director of External Affairs
until his retirement in 1992.</ul>
<p>
<dt><b><a name="Epstein">Ralph A. Epstein, M.D.<a></b>
<ul>Dr. Ralph A. Epstein is Professor of Anesthesiology at the University of Connecticut. 

In 1981,  Dr. Epstein was recruited to the <a href="http://www.uconn.edu">University of Connecticut</a> to be the founding chairman of their academic anesthesiology department, a position he held until 1994.
Dr. Epstein is known for his expertise in the technology of medical devices and in the functioning of the medical device industry.  He is currently studying the effects of organizational changes in health care on innovation in the medical device industry.  He is the author of over 50 articles covering a wide range of interests varying from scientific experimentation to commentary on medical and legal issues.


</ul>
<p>

<dt><b><a name="Gregorsky">Frank Gregorsky</a></b>
<ul>Gregorsky is a writer and policy analyst
who has worked for the
<a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov">White House,</a> the
<a href="http://thomas.loc.gov/">U.S. House of Representatives,</a> the
Hudson Institute and
the Congressional Institute.  His articles have been published in
<i>The New York Times,</i>
<i>The Washington Post,</i>
<a href="http://town.hall.org/radio/Monitor"><i>The Christian Science Monitor,</i></a>
<i><a href="/nationalreview/welcome.html">National Review</a>,</i>
<i>Crisis,</i>
<i>Privatization Review</i> and
<i>Regulation</i> magazine.</ul>

<p>

<dt><b><a name="Howe">Neil Howe</a></b>
<ul>Howe has written extensively about
budget policy and aging, attitudes toward economic growth and
social progress, the collective personalities of generations,
and the success or failure of generations in creating endowments
for their heirs.  He is co-author of
<i>On Borrowed Time</i> (with Peter G. Peterson); and
<i>Generations</i> and <i>13th-GEN</i> (both with William Strauss).</ul>

<p>

<dt><b><a name="Lawton">Barbara Lawton</a></b>
<ul>Lawton is an expert in quality management.  She
is president of the Deming Foundation and serves as Deming
Professor of Management at the 
<a href="http://boulder.colorado.edu/">University of Colorado, Boulder.</a>
She earned her bachelor of science degree in biology from
<a href="http://www.american.edu">American University</a> 
in Washington, D.C., and her master of arts and doctorate degrees in 
<a href="http://www.stat.psu.edu/stat250/">statistics</a> from
<a href="http://www.psu.edu">Penn State University</a>
and the 
<a href="http://www.uwyo.edu/">University of Wyoming,</a> 
respectively.</ul>

<p>
<dt><b><a name="Luntz">Frank I. Luntz</a></b>
<ul>Luntz is president of the Luntz Research
Companies, Inc., a survey research organization.  The author of
<i>Candidates, Consultants & Campaigns,</i> Luntz is also a
noted scholar, serving as an adjunct assistant professor at the
<a href="http://www.upenn.edu">University of Pennsylvania</a>
 and previously served on the faculty
of the <a href="gopher://gwis.circ.gwu.edu.:70/11/Academic%20Departments%20and%20Programs/Colleges/Graduate%20School%20of%20Political%20Management">Graduate School of Political Management</a> at 
<a href="http://gwis.circ.gwu.edu/">George Washington University</a>.
Luntz received his doctorate in politics in 1987 from
<a href="http://www.ox.ac.uk">Oxford University.</a></ul>

<p>
<dt><b><a name="Muris">Timothy A. Muris</a></b>
<ul>Muris is a professor of law at the 
<a href="http://www.gmu.edu/">George Mason University</a>
School of Law.  In the 
Reagan
administration, he served as executive associate director at the
<a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/White_House/EOP/html/other/OMB.html">Office of Management and Budget</a>.  He also worked for several years
at the <a href="http://www.ftc.gov/">Federal Trade Commission</a>, including serving as the director
of the Bureau of Competition.  Prior to that he was
deputy counsel for the Presidential Task Force on Regulatory
Relief led by then 
<a href="http://sunsite.unc.edu/president/bush.html">Vice President George Bush.</a>
Timothy A. Muris may be reached via e-mail at <i><a href="mailto:tmuris@gmu.edu">tmuris@gmu.edu</a>.</i></ul>
<p>

<dt><b><a name="Pitsch">Peter K. Pitsch</a></b>

<ul>Peter Pitsch is an Adjunct Fellow specializing in telecommunication law and economics.  He is also Adjunct Fellow at the <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson/">Hudson Institute</a> and an Adjunct Professor at the <a href="http://www.ll.georgetown.edu/">Georgetown University Law Center</a>.  Prior to founding his own telecommunications consulting firm in 1989, Pitsch served as Chief of Staff to Chairman Dennis R. Patrick at the Federal Communications Commission.  He is the author of the newly released, "The Innovation Age: A New Perspective on the Telecom Revolution." 
<p></ul>

<dt><b><a name="Tollison">Robert D. Tollison</a></b>

<ul>Tollison is Duncan Black Professor of Economics and
Director of the Center for Study of Public Choice at <a href="http://www.gmu.edu/">George Mason University</a> in
Fairfax, Virginia. He has previously held academic appointments at <a href="http://www.cornell.edu/">Cornell
University</a>, <a href="http://www.tamu.edu/">Texas A&M University</a>, <a href="http://www.vt.edu">Virginia Tech</a> and <a href="http://www.clemson.edu/">Clemson University</a>. Tollison
has served twice in government, once as a Senior Staff Economist on the
Presidents Council of Economic Advisors and again as Director of the Bureau of
Economics at the <a href="http://www.ftc.gov/">Federal Trade Commission</a>.</ul>

<p>

<dt><b><a name="Viscusi">W. Kip Viscusi</a></b>

<ul>Viscusi is George G. Allen Professor of Economics at <a href="http://www.duke.edu/">Duke
University</a>. His research focuses primarily on individual and societal responses
to risk and uncertainty. He has published 15 books and 166 articles, including
Reforming Product Liability. Viscusi has been a professor at <a href="http://www.nwu.edu/">Northwestern
University</a> and Dukes Fugua School of Business, as well as a visiting professor
at the <a href="http://www.uchicago.edu/">University of Chicago</a>.</ul>

<p>

<dt><b><a name="Wardell">William M. Wardell, M.D.</a></b>

<ul>Wardell is president of Protein Engineering
Corporation in Cambridge, Massachusetts, where he is responsible for the overall
task of developing biotechnology discoveries into pharmaceuticals. He is also
Adjunct Professor of Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics at <a href="http://polaris.nemc.org/tusm/">Tufts
University Medical School</a>. Wardell has also served on the faculty of the
<a href="http://www.urmc.rochester.edu/urmc/welcome.html">University of Rochester Medical Center</a> and Strong Memorial Hospital.</ul>


<p>
</body>
