<html>

<title>PRO-FAMILY TAX RELIEF</title>

<body>

<center>

<img src="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampolgn.gif">

<h1>Pro-Family Tax Relief</h1>
<h2><i>A Look at Per-Child Credits ... and the Flat Tax</i></h2>

</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>N</font>ine years ago, President Reagan's White House 
Working Group on the Family issued a report entitled, <I>The Family: 
Preserving America's Future</I>, which had as its central recommendation
a dramatic expansion in per-child tax benefits.[1] Five years later,
the bipartisan National Commission on Children (on which then-Governor
Bill Clinton served) issued a report entitled <I>Beyond Rhetoric:
A New American Agenda for Children and Families</I>, which also
had as its central recommendation a dramatic increase in per-child
tax benefits.[2]

<p>

Given that leading officials from both parties have been talking
about pro-family tax relief for nearly a decade, the current debate
over per-child tax benefits should center around this question:
does the House GOP's proposed $500 children's tax credit offer
adequate relief to America's families or should Congress instead
move in the direction of the National Commission on Children's
call for a $1,000 per-child tax credit.

<p>

Sadly, that is not the debate taking place in Washington today.
In recent months, a noisy chorus of critics and naysayers have
been raising all sorts of objections to pro-family tax relief.
Their criticisms - which are at times contradictory - advance
a number of myths.

<p>

<center><h3>The Pander Bear Myth</h3></center>

<p>

Some argue that pro-family tax relief is an extravagant political
giveaway at odds with the larger public interest.  This idea is
advanced frequently by members of the media, who realize just
how popular pro-family tax relief is.  Rather than thoughtfully
considering the merits of various tax-cutting proposals, these
reporters and pundits smugly sneer at public officials, accusing
them of &quot;pandering&quot; to middle Americans.

<p>

One does not often find himself in the position of defending
politicians, but this sort of activity must be recognized for
what it is -- an attempt by members of the liberal media elite
to make Members of Congress feel guilty about doing what the people
elected them to do.  It is the flipside to the liberal media's
reaction to politicians who advance unpopular tax increases, who
are routinely hailed as &quot;profiles in courage.&quot;

<p>

Voters see nothing courageous about broken campaign promises.
Indeed, few things have contributed more to voter cynicism than
President Bush's failure to keep his &quot;no new taxes&quot;
pledge and President Clinton's decision to abandon his promised
&quot;middle-income tax cut&quot; soon after the 1992 election.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
It is important that policy-makers<br>
view this as a debate over 'pro-family<br>
tax cuts,' not simply 'middle-income<br>
tax relief.'
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The American people strongly support pro-family tax relief.
They want to keep more of the money they earn.  They sense that
the well-being of their families -- and the well-being of the nation
-- would improve if they had greater control over their lives.

<p>

On this point, they are right. To acknowledge as much is not
pandering.

<p>

<center><h3>The Bigger Deficit Myth</h3></center>

<p>

Some say pro-family tax relief will increase the deficit and
cause interest rates to rise.  It is quite true that the deficit
would rise if a pro-family tax cut were adopted <I>by itself</I>.
It is also quite true that an increase in government borrowing
would contract the supply of funds available for private lending,
thereby putting upward pressure on interest rates.

<p>

But it is important to point out that no one is talking about
adopting a pro-family tax cut <I>by itself</I>.  All of the sponsors
of major legislation have pledged to offset pro-family tax cuts
with dollar-for-dollar reductions in government spending.

<p>

Pro-family tax cuts &quot;paid for&quot;  by spending cuts cancel
each other out on the balance sheet.  They should have no effect
on the deficit or on interest rates.

<p>

<center><h3>The No-Growth Myth</h3></center>

<p>

Another argument often raised is that pro-family tax relief won't
spur economic growth.  This concern comes from those who believe
that tax policy should serve only economic ends, that it should
steer clear of social considerations and focus exclusively on
promoting economic growth.

<p>

There are two problems with this viewpoint.  First, much of what
is called  &quot;economic growth&quot; isn't growth at all.[3]
It is a movement of economic activity from the non-market home
economy to the quantifiable market economy.  For example, when
a family that once cared for its own child enrolls the child in
a paid day care program, there is no increase in the amount of
economic activity.  There is simply a shift from the non-market
economy to the market economy.  Yet this shift is counted as 
&quot;positive&quot; economic growth even though it often has a 
&quot;negative&quot; effect on the child's well-being.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
True economic growth involves an<br>
increase in productivity, not simply<br>
in market activity. Until our nation's<br>
economic debate is built around this<br>
fact, much of what is advanced in the<br>
name of 'growth' ought not to be adopted.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

True economic growth involves an increase in <I>productivity</I>,
not simply in market activity.  Until our nation's economic debate
is built around this fact, much of what is advanced in the name
of &quot;growth&quot; ought not to be adopted.

<p>

The second problem with the &quot;pro-family tax cuts don't spur
growth&quot; myth is that it pretends that economic policy can
be separated from social policy, that the size of a family's tax
burden simply affects its economic well-being and decision-making.
The truth, of course, is that tax policy not only affects people's
economic decision-making (about working, saving, spending, investing,
etc.) but also their &quot;non-economic&quot; decision-making
(about marrying, childbearing, childrearing, etc.).

<p>

While it is true that economic policy should strive to exert
as little influence as possible over &quot;non-economic&quot;
decisions (so that, for example, people who otherwise would not
marry won't get married just for the tax breaks), it is also true
that our nation's current economic policies exert considerable
influence over &quot;non-economic&quot; decision-making and that
this influence is almost always in an <I>anti-family</I> direction.

<p>

For example, Allan Carlson of the Rockford Institute has shown
that the Social Security system has a pernicious anti-child bias
because it robs parents of the social insurance value of their
children, thereby creating a disincentive for young couples to
invest in childrearing.[4] Indeed, if Congress were to seek to
offset this bias via the tax code (which is the only apparent
option given Social Security's sacrosanct status), it would have
to raise actual per-child savings to roughly $2,100 per child.[5]
When one considers that the net value of the current child tax
exemption is less than $400 per child (for the average family)
and that the high-water mark in the current debate is an additional
$500 per-child tax credit, it is easy to see why many people are
disappointed that the proposals currently being considered aren't
even bolder -- or to use the media's phrase, more courageous.

<p>

Of course, some are reluctant to adopt even a $500 credit because
they are intimidated by the economic &quot;cost&quot; in lost
revenue to the government.  While anti-family policies that took
more than 50 years to develop cannot be wiped out in 50 (or even
100) days, it is important to recognize that there is a social
&quot;cost&quot; to inaction or compromise.  The social &quot;cost&quot;
of weak families is measured in things like divorce rates and
crime statistics.  And these social problems impose enormous economic
costs on our society and our government.  Indeed, the best way
to reduce the demand for government services is to free families
to care for themselves.  Conversely, the best way to hinder the
dismantling of the welfare state is to leave the tax burden on
families with children at or near their current levels so that
families have a difficult time taking back responsibilities from
the state.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
It is important to recognize that<br>
there is a social cost to inaction<br>
or compromise.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center><h3>The Middle-Class Only Myth</h3></center>

<p>

Should pro-family tax relief go only to middle-class taxpayers?
Some say so.

<p>

This concern makes the mistake of viewing tax issues through
the prism of class rather than through the prism of family.  It
is true that middle-class Americans often get short shrift in
current tax policy.  (For example, when combined employer-employee
payroll taxes are added to income taxes, some lower-middle-income
couples actually have a marginal tax rate comparable to 
upper-middle-income individuals in the 28 percent bracket.)

<p>

But it is even more true that families with children are shortchanged
in current tax policy.  For example, during the first four decades
after the end of WWII, the income tax burden on singles and childless
couples increased only slightly, while it increased more than
200 percent for families with two children.[6] Reagan-era reforms
helped to reverse this trend moderately, but the dramatic shift
in tax burden from non-parents to parents still dwarfs any shift
in tax burden along income lines.

<p>

Thus, it is important that policymakers view this as a debate
over &quot;pro-family tax cuts,&quot; not simply &quot;middle-income
tax relief.&quot;  This is the way both the 1986 Working Group
and the 1991 National Commission on Children saw the issue.  Indeed,
neither of these reports advocated any type of means-testing on
per-child benefits.  Both recognized that the principle being
advanced was tax relief for families of all incomes to use in
raising children, not tax relief to people who happen to fall
into an income category that everyone considers middle-class (a
category that invariably shrinks as public debate progresses).

<p>

The fact that tax relief should be first and foremost pro-family
does not mean that policymakers should be unconcerned about the
distributional impact of these cuts.  To its credit, the House
GOP plan extends relief in the form of a per-child credit rather
than an increased per-child exemption.  In actual dollar terms,
a credit provides equal relief to all taxpayers; but in 
percentage-of-tax-burden terms, it offers greater relief to working-class 
and middle-income taxpayers than to wealthier taxpayers. (Tax exemptions, 
conversely, skew savings up the income scale, offering greater per-child 
savings to those in higher brackets.)

<p>

This is not to say that tax exemptions are always inferior to
tax credits; for example, one of the virtues of the current exemption
is that its value rises if tax rates rise, thereby guaranteeing
continued horizontal tax equity between parents and non-parents
at any income level.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The best way to reduce the demand<br>
for government services is to free<br>
families to care for themselves.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Still, given the tax code's current problems, a non-means-tested
tax credit is the best mechanism for helping families with children.
Indeed, if Congress wanted to maximize its distributional bang
for buck, it might want to consider a non-refundable version of
the 1991 National Commission on Children's $1,000 credit (which
replaced the existing exemption, thereby offering $600+ in net
per-child relief to those in the 15 percent tax bracket, but less
than $300 in net per-child tax relief to those in higher tax brackets).
Moving in this direction would make it easier for Congress to
lift the existing (and newly-proposed) income caps on per-child
benefits -- a problem that definitely needs addressing since income
caps at any level produce marriage penalties.

<p>

Speaking of marriage penalties, the income caps on the Earned
Income Tax Credit have created such a serious anti-marriage effect
that Congress should use all of the monies set aside in the marriage
penalty section of the American Dream Restoration Act to address
the marriage bias facing families earning below the median income.
The Talent-Faircloth welfare reform initiative from 1994 called
for a $1,000 pro-marriage tax credit.  This would be a constructive,
problem-solving first step.  It ought to be adopted.

<p>

<center><h3>The Can't Trust Parents Myth</h3></center>

<p>

Some believe pro-family tax relief should tie benefits to family
expenses (like education) that the government should promote.
This concern springs from the notion that the government knows
more about what families should spend their money for than parents
do.

<p>

Not only is this a false premise, but it leads to all sorts of
unproductive economic distortions.  Indeed, one of the chief reasons
college tuition costs have been rising at a pace exceeding the
general inflation rate is that many students have been given grants
and loans that could be used only for educational purposes.  Knowing
this to be the case, college administrators have raised the cost
of higher education beyond what it would be if students' economic
resources were completely fungible and available for multiple
uses.

<p>

While no one wants to discourage bright young people from pursuing
a higher education, the sad truth is that tax cuts earmarked for
this or any other family expense will have the effect of increasing
the cost of that good or service, thereby exacerbating current
problems and putting a college education out of the reach of some
interested students.  In addition, tax deductions keyed to college
tuition expenses benefit students attending higher-priced schools
more than other students.

<p>

While it would be counter-productive for Congress to provide
tax cuts for specific expenses, it would be helpful for Congress
to modify existing Individual Retirement Account (IRA) rules to
permit taxpayers to enjoy tax-favored savings for a wider variety
of purposes (college tuition, first-time home-buying, etc.). 
In the first case, Congress would be limiting families' economic
freedom, in the second, it would be expanding it.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Few things have contributed more to<br>
voter cynicism than President Bush's<br>
failure to keep his no new taxes pledge<br>
and President Clinton's decision to<br>
abandon his promised middle-income tax<br>
cut soon after the 1992 election.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

This is not to say, however, that the Super IRA included in the
House GOP Contract should be adopted in its current form.  The
&quot;back-loaded&quot; nature of its design obligates future
generations to an economic promise made today.  Given the size
of the federal debt, and the pernicious anti-family influence
of intergenerational entitlement programs, Congress should steer
clear of repeating past mistakes.  If tax-favored savings are
to be expanded, they should be expanded within the context of
a &quot;front-loaded&quot; savings mechanism.

<p>

<center><h3>Armey's Flat Tax Appeal</h3></center>

<p>

While the proposed increase in per-child tax benefits is commanding
center stage in the current debate, there is growing interest
in a flat tax proposal sponsored by House GOP Minority Leader
Dick Armey.  The Armey proposal, which some Republicans want to
make a central plank in the 1996 GOP campaign platform, would
reduce the federal income tax form to the size of a post card
by eliminating all existing deductions, exemptions, and credits.
Thus, after claiming &quot;personal allowances&quot; (which allow
taxpayers to adjust their tax liability for family size), all
taxpayers would pay income taxes at a 17 percent marginal rate.

<p>

As such, the Armey plan has a number of appealing features.
These include:

<ul><p>

<li><b><i>Simplicity</i></b>.  Despite periodic attempts to make
tax filing easier, America's tax code is
littered with so many cumbersome rules, regulations, and stipulations
that many ordinary taxpayers feel justifiably overwhelmed.  Eliminating
the tax code's complexity would reduce errors and encourage respect
for and compliance with the code.  It would also free people to
make more productive use of the time they now devote to income
tax compliance.  According to economist Walter Williams of George
Mason University, Americans spend more than six billion hours
each year on record keeping, tax planning, and tax return preparation.
If those same hours were spent producing useful things, Williams
says they would be equal to the combined output of our auto, truck,
and aircraft industries.[7]

<p>

<li><b><i>No Withholding</i></b>.  Rather than continuing the
current system of having employers
withhold income taxes from employees' wages, the Armey plan would
permit taxpayers to take home their entire gross earnings and
then make a monthly tax payment to the government (much as they
currently make a monthly mortgage payment to their lending company).
Eliminating wage withholding would free employers from burdensome
administrative paperwork -- and would help taxpayers see just how
large their tax bite is.  Nothing fosters high taxes more than
the fact that they are currently &quot;hidden&quot; from full
view by wage withholding.  Were all earnings to &quot;pass through&quot;
taxpayers' wallets, Americans would undoubtedly become more aware
of their current tax burden -- and of any changes to it in the
future.

<p>

<li><b><i>Reduced Marriage Penalty</i></b>.  The Armey plan eliminates
most existing marriage penalties in the current income tax code by 
offering marrieds a personal allowance twice that of singles and by 
eliminating all tax rate progressivity. (By retaining the &quot;head of 
household&quot; filing category for single parents, the marriage penalty 
is not eliminated altogether.)  Given the size of the current penalty
(particularly among the working poor) and the larger cultural
need to strengthen the institution of marriage, the Armey plan's
improved treatment of marriage compares well to current law.

<p>

<li><b><i>No Junk</i></b>.  While there is a case to be made for
tax simplification for simplification's
sake, the Armey plan's eradication of existing deductions and
credits has the added virtue of eliminating many ill-conceived
tax write-offs.  For example, the deductibility of state and local
taxes has the effect of redistributing income from people living
in low-tax areas to people living in high-tax states.  Similarly,
the dependant care tax credit has the effect of redistributing
income from families that care for their own children to families
that enroll their children in day care.  Eliminating such write-offs
would eliminate economic distortions and perverse social incentives.

<p>

<li><b><i>Generous Family Benefits</i></b>.  The Armey plan proposes
personal allowances of $13,100
for singles, $26,200 for marrieds, and $5,300 for each dependent
child.  As such, a typical family of four would not begin paying
income taxes until it has earned $36,800 in income.  Although
these family benefits are less generous than those which existed
in the late 1940s and early 1950s, they are considerably higher
than current thresholds (which shield a family of four's first
$16,150 from income taxation).

</ul><p>

<center><h3>Challenges for The Armey Approach</h3></center>

<p>

While the Armey plan has many appealing features, it also faces
a number of challenges -- challenges that will need to be addressed
before the Armey plan (or any variation of it) can be adopted.
These include:

<p><ul>

<li><b><i>Doesn't The Federal Government Already Have An Effective
Flat Tax?</i></b> Most &quot;flat
tax&quot; proponents think only in terms of leveling federal
income taxes.  But America's taxpayers not only pay federal income
taxes but also federal payroll taxes.  The combined employer-employee
share of payroll taxes is just over 15 percent for taxpayers earning
up to $60,600.  This means that most working-class and middle-income
families have a combined marginal tax rate of roughly 30 percent
(divided almost equally between payroll and income taxes).  This
amount is comparable to the marginal tax rate of upper-middle-income
taxpayers in the 28 and 31 percent income tax brackets.

<p>

If Congress were to adopt the Armey plan, and to leave in place
the existing payroll tax, taxpayers in the current 15 percent
income tax bracket would see their combined marginal tax rate
rise to over 32 percent (because Armey replaces the 15 percent
rate with a 17 percent rate).  Meanwhile, upper-middle-income
taxpayers (whose incomes exceed the current cap on payroll taxes)
would experience a dramatic reduction in marginal tax rates from
28 and 31 percent to 17 percent.

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Nothing fosters high taxes more<br>
than the fact that they are<br>
currently hidden from full<br>
view by wage witholding.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

Armey proponents choose not to address the payroll tax question,
arguing that social security &quot;contributions&quot; should
be viewed as mandatory payments to a pension plan rather than
taxes to support a cash transfer program.  Given that taxpayers
have no control of these &quot;mandatory payments,&quot; Congress
should alter the construct of the Armey plan so that it takes
payroll taxes into consideration.  This would ensure that taxpayers
earning below $60,600 would not have higher marginal tax rates
than those making above $60,600.

<p>

<li><b><i>Doesn't Rate Progressivity Offset The Anti-Family Aspects
Of The Social Security System?</i></b> Allan Carlson of the Rockford 
Institute argues that &quot;the effect of a flat income tax rate at levels
above 10 percent is to weaken the family as an economic unit.&quot;[8]
Carlson believes a progressive income tax is preferable because
rate progressivity encourages non-market home production over
market production.  Given that the long-term health of our society
(and, for that matter, the long-term health of our economy) would
be threatened by the shift of certain responsibilities from families
and volunteer associations to the market economy, Carlson believes
taxwriters should attempt to make the tax code more progressive
rather than less.  (He would take the revenues generated by greater
progressivity and devote them to a $1,500 per-child credit and
a revival of income-splitting to solve the marriage penalty problem.)

<p>

While Carlson's call for greater progressivity is unlikely to
find an audience with most GOP policymakers, it is important to
point out that the case for a flat tax is seriously weakened by
the social security system's anti-child bias.  If there were no
social security system, parents would have a natural economic
incentive to invest in childrearing because their economic security
in old age would be directly linked to their children's future
productivity.  In other words, in a world without social security,
the workaholic who neglects his childrearing responsibilities
puts himself at risk in old age because his children may turn
out to be dolts or sloths incapable of offering him support if
needed.

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The case for a flat tax is<br>
seriously weakened by the social<br>
security system's anti-child bias.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

In a world with social security, however, the workaholic who
neglects his childrearing responsibilities puts himself at no
such risk.  If his kids turn out to be unproductive, he does not
suffer -- so long as there are plenty of well-reared children from
other families capable of keeping the system afloat.

<p>

Thankfully, economic incentives are not the only factors -- or
even the primary factors -- influencing parental investments in
children.  Moral imperatives still carry much sway.

<p>

But lest anyone think economic factors are irrelevant, consider
how often one hears talk today from families that say they &quot;can't
afford another child&quot; or &quot;can't afford to have one parent
stay home with young children because they have to have two paychecks.&quot;

<p>

In the abstract, one can easily make a case that an ideal economic
system would have neither a progressive income tax nor an old-age
social insurance scheme.

<p>

Given that no modification in social security is being proposed,
proponents of the Armey flat tax must explain how they would propose
to counteract policy-based incentives for parents to neglect their
non-market childrearing duties.

<p>

<li><b><i>How Does Eliminating Charitable Contributions Square
With A Larger Social Vision That Wants To Replace Government Welfare 
With Private Charity?</i></b> 
To their credit, most proponents of the Armey flat tax are also
advocates of limited government who would like to see the welfare
state dismantled and replaced by private charity.  While this
philosophy does not obligate one to support the continuation
of tax write-offs for charitable contributions, it may be asking
too much to expect the American people simultaneously to support
an elimination of charitable tax deductions and a dismantling
of government welfare programs.  Given the serious social problems
associated with government welfare programs, Congress should do
nothing that might have the effect of undermining public support
for dismantling the welfare state.  Not only does this argue for
the retention of charitable contributions, it actually argues
for an expansion of them.

<p>

Here again, the question is not necessarily one of what is best
in the abstract.  The question, instead, is whether the goal of
a deduction-free tax code should supersede all other goals -- including
the goal of shifting welfare responsibilities from the state to
the charitable sector.

<p>

<li><b><i>How Will Eliminating The Deductibility Of Mortgage Interest
Affect Property Values And The Real Net Worth Of Families?</i></b> Just 
as charitable contributions present a dilemma to Armey flat tax 
proponents, so too do home mortgage interest payments.

<p>

While the intellectual case for mortgage interest deductions
is far weaker than for charitable contributions -- in fact, Carlson
argues that mortgage interest deductions have had an anti-family
effect by encouraging smaller households and spurring artificial
growth in housing prices[9] -- the problem is that eliminating the
mortgage interest deduction that is now in place could have an
even more serious anti-family effect.  Many families have a considerable
share of their entire net worth tied up in their homes.  If a
proposal eliminating the mortgage interest deduction were to pass,
and thereby to pull the rug out from under property owners, the
social and economic effects could be quite serious.  Indeed, the
recession that occurred during the Bush Administration was caused
in part by a decline in home values.  As families saw their net
worth falling, they understandably felt less freedom to make new
purchases.

<p>

It is possible, as Armey proponents maintain, that the negative
effect on property values of eliminating home mortgage deductibility
will be offset by the positive effect of greater economic growth
in other parts of the economy.  But it is also quite possible
that consumers will respond to the elimination of home mortgage
deductibility in the same manner they responded to the housing
recession of the late 1980s.

<p>

Given that those who have the most to lose from instability in
the housing market are young families who have recently purchased
first homes, Congress must proceed very cautiously in this area.

<p>

<li><b><i>Won't The Value Of Pro-Family Benefits Decline As The
Legislative Process Unfolds?</i></b> As noted earlier, the Armey tax 
plan includes
adjustments for family size that exceed current law.  While this
is one of the plan's most laudable features, there is reason to
believe that the benefit levels leaving the starting gate of the
legislative process would never survive the marathon to the finish
line.  The reason is simple:  if any change is made in the Armey
plan that would have the effect of reducing revenues (such as
reinserting certain tax write-offs) the only options Armey would
have would be:

<p><ul>

(1)  to increase the deficit;<br>
(2)  to raise the tax rate above 17 percent; or<br>
(3)  to reduce family benefits.

</ul><p>

The first option would be unlikely in any scenario, but is especially
so given that Armey's proposal, by his own estimates, would raise
$40 billion less than current law (and some claim the shortfall
would be as much as four times this amount).  Indeed, given the
level of concern that has already arisen about revenue shortfalls,
it is quite possible that family tax benefits could be raided
even if no other changes were made to the Armey plan.

<p>

The second option -- raising the tax rate above 17 percent -- is
also unlikely because the political support for the flat tax largely
hangs or falls on the size of this number.  Tax policy is mysterious
to most Americans.  Average citizens are far more likely to follow
fluctuations in the flat rate structure than fluctuations in the
family benefits -- especially since the premise of the debate is
that we need a flat <I>rate</I>.

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Those who believe the most serious<br>
problem in the current tax code is<br>
the absence of significant pro-family<br>
benefits are poorly served by a debate<br>
that emphasizes rates rather than the<br>
size of the pro-family benefits.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

Thus, those who believe the most serious problem in the current
tax code is the absence of significant pro-family benefits are
poorly served by a debate that emphasizes rates rather than the
size of pro-family benefits.

<p>

Indeed, one of the virtues of the existing debate surrounding
the House GOP's Contract proposal is that it has centered around
the $500 per-child figure.  While this amount should be higher,
it will be difficult for Members of Congress to pass something
less than this amount without having to do an awful lot of explaining
to their constituents. Hopefully, Armey proponents can find
a way to offer this level of protection to pro-family benefits
during the legislative process.

</ul><p>

<center><h3>Family First</h3></center>

<p>

After years of talk but no action on the pro-family tax front,
Congress appears poised to finally adopt some significant per-child
relief.  This is long overdue.  In 1948, a median income family
of four sent two percent of its annual income to the federal government
in federal income and payroll taxes.  Today, that same family
sends 24.5 percent of its income to the Federal Treasury.[10] The
erosion in the value of per-child benefits is the primary reason
for this dramatic increase in the income tax burden of America's
families.  According to Eugene Steuerle of the Urban Institute,
the current child exemption would need to be quadrupled in size
in order to offset the same percentage of income that the exemption
shielded from taxation in 1948.[11]

<p>

Given the magnitude of this historic shift, nothing -- including
the possibility of making even more dramatic tax changes in the
near future -- should deter Congress from adopting at least $500
in per-child tax savings.

<p><hr><p>

<hr width=60% noshade><p>

<center>

<h2>A CLOSER LOOK</h2>

<p><hr width=60% noshade><p>

<h2>The Limits of Tax Relief</h2>

</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>W</font>hile it is important for Members of Congress to 
recognize the virtues of pro-family tax relief, it is also important 
for them to recognize the limitations of pro-family relief.

<p>

Pro-family tax relief will not make husbands love their wives
or children respect their parents.  It will not clear up filthy
TV or remove child predators from our streets.  In short, pro-family
tax relief, by itself, will not magically solve the myriad social
problems facing America's families, neighborhoods, and communities.

<p>

But pro-family tax relief will make it easier for families to
thrive by reducing economic stress.  It will make it easier for
parent
them from other harms by freeing them to spend more of their time
with their children and less of their time frantically chasing
the almighty, overtaxed dollar.

<p>

In short, pro-family tax relief will empower parents to address
many family needs that only they can meet.

<p>

America needs parents who want to raise their children well.
But we also need policies that empower them to act upon these
sentiments.

<p>

The 104th Congress should adopt nothing less than $500 in per-child
tax relief for all taxpaying families.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>- by William R. Mattox, Jr.<br>
Vice President for Policy</i>

<p><hr><p>

<font size=-1><center>

