<title>FREEING AMERICA'S SCHOOLS</title>

<body>

<center>

<img src="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampolbl.gif">

<h1>Freeing America's Schools</h1>
<h2><i>The Case Against the U.S. Education Department</i></h2>

</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>A</font> century and a half ago, Alexis de 
Tocqueville recognized that increased centralization and 
bureaucratization saps civic and individual responsibility. 
"[A] centralized administration is fit only to enervate the 
nations in which it exists, by incessantly diminishing their 
local spirit",[1] wrote Tocqueville.

<p>

Cathy Duffy, in a new book titled <i>Government Nannies</i>, 
echoes Tocqueville's observation: "History and common sense 
tell us that people are more likely to assume responsibility 
when they know that no one else will.  If I knew that no one 
else was going to watch my car's gas gauge and remind me to 
fill the tank before it hits empty, I would do it myself.  
But my husband watches it closely and puts gas in the car for 
me.  As a result of his kindness, I rarely look at the gas gauge."[2]

<p>

Unfortunately, many Americans seem to have forgotten this principle 
and have yielded responsibility for certain domestic functions to 
central planners working in the federal government.  Nowhere is 
this more apparent than in the area of education, where increased 
bureaucratic control has bred local apathy which, in turn, has bred 
greater bureaucratic control.  Indeed, many contemporary Americans 
resemble the 19th century European described by Tocqueville:

<p>

<blockquote><i>

The condition of his village, the police of his street, the 
repairs of the church or the parsonage, do not concern him; 
for he looks upon all these things as unconnected with himself 
and as the property of a powerful stranger whom he calls the 
government....  This want of interest in his own affairs goes 
so far that if his own safety or that of his children is at last 
endangered, instead of trying to avert the peril, he will fold 
his arms and wait till the whole nation comes to his aid....</i>[3]

</blockquote>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
In the area of education, increased<br>
bureaucratic control has bred local<br>
apathy which, in turn, has bred<br>
greater bureaucratic control.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Tocqueville warns that, when a nation reaches this point, 
"it must either change its customs and its laws, or perish; 
for the source of public virtues is dried up; and though it 
may contain subjects, it has no citizens."[4]

<p>

<center><h3>Ending the Federal Role in Education</h3></center>

<p>

The United States Constitution is a document of enumerated powers. 
That is, the Federal government is permitted to do only what the 
Constitution specifically lists.  This is expressed clearly and 
succinctly in the 10th amendment:   "The powers not delegated to 
the Constitution, nor prohibited by it to the States, are reserved 
to the States respectively, or to the people."

<p>

Since education is not listed as a Federal responsibility, it was 
exclusively under the jurisdiction of states and localities through 
most of our history.  Things began to change in the 1930s when the 
New Deal brought increasing Federal involvement.  Later, under 
Eisenhower, a cabinet-level department was created:  Health, 
Education and Welfare.  And under the Johnson Administration, 
passage of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act expanded 
federal involvement further.

<p>

Then, in 1976, Democratic presidential nominee Jimmy Carter 
promised the creation of a separate education department if 
elected and received the backing of the National Education 
Association (NEA) as a result.  In 1979, President Carter set 
about to make good on his promise.  But there was strong opposition 
from the American Federation of Teachers (the second-largest teacher 
union), from much of higher education, and from the general public. 
The AFL-CIO attacked the idea[5] and even the liberal <i>Washington 
Post</i> argued that "shifting federal education programs to a 
separate department increases bureaucratic costs."[6]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Hawaiians could manage these<br>
programs more efficiently and<br>
less expensively than the federal<br>
government. And if Hawaiians, then<br>
why not Carolinians, Vermonters,<br>
and Texans, as well?
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Many Americans feared that a cabinet-level department would 
lead to an expanded federal role in education.  Marvin Stone, 
in an editorial in <i>U.S. News & World Report</i>, put it 
this way:   Would the Education Department have the power to 
tamper with America's traditional local control of education? 
Of course it would.  Where there is money to be given, there 
is the implicit responsibility to make sure that it is spent 
according to the purposes of the donors  -- or else.[7]

<p>

While the bill establishing the department stated emphatically 
that the Department would not undermine state and local control, 
Stone noted:

<p>

<blockquote><i>

...a subtle schizophrenia, meandering through the legislation and 
the committee appraisal, suggests that the authors' inward dream 
for the department runs at odds with the stated restrictions. One 
keeps encountering such phrases as  "implement...at the local level" 
...  "assesses the achievement of federal objectives" ... and 
"monitoring parental and public participation."</i>[8]

</blockquote>

<p>

Today, Stone's essay seems prophetic.  The <i>Guide to U.S. 
Department of Education Programs</i> lists 241 separate programs, 
many of which have usurped the prerogatives of the states.  For 
example, the index identifies six programs exclusively for Native 
Hawaiians.  It is instructive to imagine tax monies garnered in 
Oahu, transferred to a federal bureaucracy 6,000 miles away, 
filtered expensively through Washington's education blob, and the 
remainder returned to the island state for Native Hawaiian 
education.  It is not difficult to believe that Hawaiians could 
manage these programs more efficiently and less expensively than 
the federal government.  And if Hawaiians, then why not Carolinians, 
Vermonters, and Texans as well?

<p>

The U.S. Education Department, then, is an entity with a dubious 
past.  Its conception was of doubtful legitimacy, given the 
strictures of Constitution and tradition.  The circumstances 
of its birth were suspect -- more or less a political payoff 
to the NEA.  Furthermore, the U.S. Education Department has 
not improved American education.

<p>

Before its creation, President Carter could point to  "[o]ur 
Nation's pluralistic education system" as "the most competent 
and open in the world...."[9] No longer so.  According to 
former Secretary of Education William Bennett, more than 90 
percent of the students entering U.S. colleges would not be 
admitted to post-secondary education anywhere else in the world.[10] 
The 1990 National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) declared 
that as many as half of elementary and secondary students do not 
demonstrate  "competency in challenging subject matter in English, 
mathematics, science, history, and geography.  Further, even fewer 
are able to use their minds well."[11]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The U.S. Education Department<br>
has elbowed its way into places<br>
it does not belong.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Meanwhile, the U.S. Education Department has grown into a huge 
bureaucratic blob.  It has elbowed its way into places it does 
not belong, not the least of which are local schools and family 
life.

<p>

<center><h3>Goals 2000</h3></center>

<p>

On March 31, 1994, federal intrusiveness reached a new height with 
passage of Goals 2000.  Groundwork for the program was being laid 
as early as 1987 when Richard Riley and Hillary Rodham Clinton 
served on the Southern Regional Education Board's (SREB) Commission 
on Educational Quality.  Bill Clinton also participated in SREB 
meetings.  The commission developed a set of goals and published 
<i>Goals for Education:  Challenge 2000</i> in 1988.[12] In 1989, 
President Bush summoned the nation's governors to an educational 
summit meeting in Charlottesville, Virginia.  At this gathering, 
then-Governor Clinton played a major role in leading the governors 
to adopt six ambitious national goals for education.  These goals 
formed the basis of America 2000, President Bush's plan for 
education reform.

<p>

The America 2000 plan represented a dramatic departure from 
the American political tradition in education, as explained 
by John F. Jennings, director of the Center on National 
Education Policy:

<p>

<blockquote><i>

Democratic Presidents Kennedy and Johnson had proposed a major 
expansion of federal aid to education in the 1960s and had 
achieved the enactment of historic legislation that created 
the current array of federal programs.  But they were dogged 
along the way by criticism from conservatives who asserted that 
the liberals were really trying to nationalize education.  Now, 
25 years later, it was a self-proclaimed conservative Republican, 
not a liberal Democrat, who was advocating <b>a monumental 
movement away from local control of education</b>.</i>[13] 
<i>(emphasis added)

</i></blockquote>

<p>

While Bush failed to get both Houses of Congress to adopt his 
plan, President Clinton was quick to seize the initiative on 
this issue soon after his election in 1992.  Clinton expanded 
Bush's plan, renamed it Goals 2000, and made it the cornerstone 
of his Education Department's agenda.

<p>

The reach of Goals 2000 as educational innovation can hardly be 
overstated.  Albert Shanker of the American Federation of 
Teachers called it  "the most important piece of education 
legislation we've ever had."[14] And Secretary of Education 
Richard Riley wrote,  "For the first time in the nation's 
history, a statutory framework defining an appropriate role 
for the federal government has been enacted."[15]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Goals 2000 includes national<br>
education goals and standards<br>
that override local priorities<br>
and ignore the fact that many<br>
private entities have developed<br>
standards for student learning.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Goals 2000 provides a framework for restructuring the American 
system of education, creating tighter and more definite links 
between the federal, state and local levels.  This makes it 
even easier for the Education Department to tamper with local 
schools than Marvin Stone once envisioned.

<p>

Indeed, Goals 2000 includes national education goals and standards 
that override local priorities and ignore the fact that many 
private entities have developed standards for student learning. 
E.D. Hirsch, for example, has written a series of books on cultural 
literacy, describing fundamentals of education at each grade level. 
The Family Research Council has published an outline of U.S. history 
entitled <i>Let Freedom Ring</i>. William Bennett's best-selling 
<i>Book of Virtues</i> is a wonderful source of America's literary 
heritage.  All of these examples meet the need for high academic 
standards.

<p>

What is revolutionary about Goals 2000 is the idea that the federal 
government should be involved in creating and certifying standards 
for education and in determining  "official knowledge."

<p>

The goals, themselves, are highly problematic.  First, they smack 
of Utopianism.  They illustrate the 
"with-a-stroke-of-this-pen-I-change-the-world" kind of thought that 
sometimes afflicts high-level bureaucrats and politicians. For 
example,[16] Goal Six says that every adult American will be 
literate.  Since some estimates put the number of adult illiterates 
at nearly four million and the number of functional illiterates at 
30 million, their re-education would require a national mobilization 
akin to fighting World War I.  And these are <b>adults</b> -- 
outside the scope of compulsory education.  Goals like this with 
a timetable like this (all problems solved in six years!) are so 
unrealistic as to undermine public confidence in the politicians 
and the educational establishment.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
'National standards' could<br>
actually work to 'dumb down'<br>
educational expectations<br>
rather than to raise them.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The goals also have coercive implications.  Goal One says "all 
children in America will start school ready to learn."  Assuming 
the statement is not mere rhetoric, how will the government meet 
this goal?  Or consider Goal Eight:   "Every school will promote 
partnerships that will increase parental involvement and 
participation in promoting the social, emotional, and academic 
growth of children."  Note the peremptory  "will": these 
"partnerships" are not optional.  They instruct school officials 
to direct parents rather than stating that parents are to be 
primarily responsible for their children's education. Moreover, 
Goals 2000 defines parental involvement in mostly peripheral 
terms: parent-teacher conferences, PTA meetings, etc.

<p>

Goal Three says that "American students will leave grade four, 
eight, and twelve having demonstrated competency in challenging 
subject matter...."  Who decides what  "challenging subject matter" 
is, and what is  "demonstrated competency" over it?  The Goals 2000 
law created a new federal agency, the National Educational Standards 
and Improvement Council (NESIC).  Under the law, states may draw up 
state educational standards or use the national standards that will 
also be made available.  All of this was declared, in the Goals 2000 
law itself, to be entirely voluntary.  Indeed, among its supporters, 
Goals 2000 is hardly mentioned without the assuring  "voluntary" 
prefix.  Calling it  "voluntary" is actually highly misleading, 
especially in light of other legislation.  As Secretary of Education 
Richard Riley said of the Goals 2000 law,  "We were determined that 
Goals 2000 become the prism through which amendments to every other 
program in elementary and secondary education would be considered."[17]

<p>

One such program is the Elementary and Secondary Education Act 
(ESEA), under which 90 percent of the schools in the nation 
receive funding.  Under <i>this</i> law states cannot receive federal 
funding for elementary and secondary education unless they follow 
an application process nearly identical to that contained in Goals 
2000.  In fact the ESEA declares that  "[i]f a State has State 
content standards or State student performance standards developed 
under title III of the Goals 2000:  Educate America Act and an 
aligned set of assessments...the State shall use such standards 
and assessments"[18] as its plan to be submitted for application 
purposes.

<p>

Some argue that Goals 2000 is voluntary because states are free to 
write standards of their own.  The catch is that even these state 
standards must be approved by the U.S. Department of Education in 
order for the state to receive Goals 2000 funds.  What kind of 
standards are the feds likely to approve?  Since there will be 
federal standards and curriculum for each discipline, no state 
will be left guessing.  And no one who understands human nature 
will be left guessing about what all the states' materials will 
tend to look like. "National standards" sounds challenging: 
they aren't. The U.S. Education Department, for example, recently 
sued Ohio for imposing an eighth grade reading requirement as a 
condition of high school graduation. The standard was too 
restrictive, too discriminatory. Thus, "national standards" 
could actually work to  "dumb down" educational expectations, 
rather than to raise them.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The history standards are<br>
replete with political<br>
correctness: Paul Revere,<br>
Thomas Edison, the Wright<br>
Brothers, Alexander Graham<br>
Bell, Robert E. Lee, and<br>
Albert Einstein are all<br>
omitted; yet, Madonna, Speckled<br>
Snake, and The Simpsons are<br>
included.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center><h3>Faulty Standards</h3></center>

<p>

Consider the U.S. history standards, written by the Center for 
History in the Schools at UCLA under a $2 million grant from the 
U.S. Education Department and the National Endowment for the 
Humanities.  They contain many historical facts and interesting 
teaching strategies.  But nothing could better demonstrate the 
dangers of a national curriculum.  The standards are replete 
with political correctness.  Paul Revere, Thomas Edison, J.P. 
Morgan, the Wright Brothers, Alexander Graham Bell, Robert E. 
Lee, and Albert Einstein are all omitted; yet, Madonna, Speckled 
Snake and The Simpsons are included.

<p>

The standards not only trivialize American history, but also 
present an exceedingly gloomy view of America.  Nobody wants 
a history written through rose-colored glasses --  but the 
standards go beyond an honest appraisal of national failures, 
replacing  "America: land of opportunity," with  "America: land 
of oppression."  As Albert Shanker pointed out, no other 
government has tried to teach its children to have negative 
feelings about their own country.[19]

<p>

Political correctness also colors many of the questions and 
assignments in the history standards.  For example, students 
are asked to  "explain how feminism was compelling in its 
analysis of women's problems and solutions offered."  To the 
ideologically charged individuals who wrote the standards, 
feminist ideology could only be  "compelling."  But for many 
Americans, this premise is highly debatable.  That there is 
such a disagreement should not be a problem.  Histories should 
acknowledge diversity of opinion, instead of pretending that all 
people hold the same views.  It is highly ironic that those whose 
very creed is  "diversity" should seek to ignore and marginalize 
opinion when it differs from their own.

<p>

Another weakness of the standards has been little noted in the 
national discussion:  they contain virtually no explanation of 
what communism is and what it did.  It is difficult to see how 
any student could make sense of the 20th century without 
understanding what Marx and Lenin taught and how Stalin acted 
on those teachings.  The Cold War for example -- nearly half a 
century of American history -- becomes inexplicable.  During this 
century, Soviet Communism was responsible for at least 60 million 
deaths.  Adding Communist China brings the toll to many millions 
more.  Without an understanding of this, the student could only 
consider the collision of democracy and Communism to be like some 
pointless dynastic or boundary-marker squabble of the distant past.

<p>

Indeed, the history standards implicitly subscribe to the doctrine 
of moral equivalence, describing the Cold War merely as "swordplay 
of the Soviet Union and the United States," and making no mention of 
Soviet invasions of Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Afghanistan.  They 
describe  "Soviet advances in space" and the <i>Challenger</i> 
disaster, while omitting any reference to John Glenn or the successful 
U.S. moon landing.  Columnist George Will says they show a "cranky 
anti-Americanism."[20]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
It is ironic that those<br>
whose very creed is<br>
'diversity' seek to ignore<br>
and marginalize opinion when<br>
it differs from their own.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

How is it possible that a program like Goals 2000 -- quite inimical 
to American tradition -- has become the manual for running local 
schools?  Partly, as we have seen, through subterfuge: the 
insistent repetition that it is entirely voluntary.  Partly because 
the profound crisis of American education has convinced many that 
only an enormous federal initiative can cope with it.  But this 
conviction is based on the fallacy that the federal government has 
money of its own.  In reality, the only money the U.S. Education 
Department has is money that citizens once earned.  Think back to 
the example of the federal programs for Native Hawaiians.  They 
typify every federal education program:  the money localities give 
up to Washington is returned to them -- much diminished.  The 
total U.S. Education Department budget has reached a level of $30 
billion dollars.  What if this money were simply routed to the local 
schools instead of being routed through the federal bureaucracy? It 
tickles the imagination to think of the textbooks and desks and 
computers and art classes and chemistry labs and gymnasiums and 
field trips and new teachers that could be financed with the savings.

<p>

There would be another great advantage for localities if the 
federal government got out of the education business.  There 
is a misperception that Washington provides the lion's share 
of education funding in this nation.  In reality, federal 
spending accounts for only about 6.5 percent[21] of the funding 
that goes into local education. Yet, "Uncle Sam's leverage 
over U.S. education is greater than his six or seven percent of 
the school budget would indicate," notes Chester Finn, former 
assistant secretary of education under President Reagan.[22] 
Overbearing federal regulations hinder local school freedom. 
Getting the federal education bureaucracy out of our pockets 
and off our backs should liberate local leaders and infuse 
communities with a new sense of local spirit.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The history standards describe<br>
'Soviet advances in space' and<br>
the Challenger disaster, while<br>
omitting any reference to John<br>
Glenn or the successful U.S.<br>
moon landing.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

President Carter, arguing in 1979 for the establishment of a U.S. 
Education Department, boasted: "Under the proposal I am submitting 
today, the Department of Education will include more than 150 programs 
and 16,200 employees.  With a budget of more than $13 billion, this 
Department will be larger than five other Departments including Energy, 
Commerce, Justice, Interior and State."[23] Such was the sentiment with 
which the U.S. Education Department was formed.  Few politicians would 
dare to highlight these facts today.  In its 15 years of existence the 
U.S. Education Department has added 100 programs, more than doubled its 
annual expenditures, and doubled its outlays as a percentage of total 
federal spending, from one percent to two percent.[24] In hindsight, 
it is clear that enlarging the federal role in education was a mistake. 
As early as 1981, policy analysts recognized that "the creation of this 
Department was a mistake, that its enactment is analogous to an inversion 
of the proverbial miller's tale, spinning something fine back into 
something coarse."[25] The federal government should no longer have a 
role in American education.

<p>

<center><h3>Common Objections</h3></center>

<p>

Some argue that the U.S. Education Department must be preserved 
because of four seemingly critical functions of the federal department: 
helping the disabled, protecting civil rights, providing college loans, 
and conducting national educational research.  But there is reason to 
believe that these functions can be handled by state and local 
governments and by private entities.  Indeed, one-size-fits-all 
administrative policies handed down by the federal government have 
often proved counter-productive.  Consider, for example, special 
education.

<p>

The federal government's spending on special education accounts for 
a very small percentage of the cost of educating each student with 
disabilities -- only eight percent.  Yet, its regulations define the 
special education policies which local schools must follow.

<p>

The Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) began two 
decades ago with the purpose of providing all children with handicaps 
a "free and appropriate public education."  After many reauthorizations 
and amendments, the federal special education requirements are now 
numerous, detailed and cumbersome.  Schools are instructed to place 
students in the  "least restrictive environment."  Today this policy 
is defined as full inclusion.  That means that the regular classroom 
must be the first option for all children with handicaps, and many in 
the education establishment, ignoring the fact that diverse needs require 
diverse solutions, are determined to make the regular classroom the "best 
option" by bringing in aides, special materials, equipment, etc.[26] As 
Albert Shanker has said,  "The argument on the part of inclusionists 
rests on the social benefits of education.  Some have even stated that 
they don't care if other children don't learn to read and write, if 
they have learned to 'get along.'"[27]

<p>

The federally mandated policy of inclusion presents an excellent 
example of why a federal Education Department is ineffective and 
inappropriate.  A single national policy cannot meet the needs of 
all students.  Nowhere is this more true than in special education, 
where a student's learning depends largely on how closely teaching 
methods meet his or her needs.  Those closest to the student with 
special needs -- parents and teachers -- should have authority to 
shape policy so it will be appropriate for that student.

<p>

Just as the U.S. Department of Education is poorly suited to the 
task of setting special education policies, it is poorly suited 
to the task of protecting the civil rights of students.

<p>

Civil rights issues in schools today are not significantly different 
from those in any other arena of American life.  To guarantee 
students equal protection under the law, the function of preserving 
civil rights in schools should be moved to the U.S. Justice Department. 
Schools have broken the chains of discrimination, and minority students 
have made considerable progress as a result.  Indeed, one of the few 
success stories in American education in the last three decades is the 
reduced disparity in the relative achievement and graduation rates of 
white and minority students.[28]

<p>

In dealing with schools, the Justice Department must heed the advice 
given in 1981 to the Office of Civil Rights (OCR) in the Education 
Department:

<p>

<blockquote><i>

The civil rights of individuals are fundamental, and should not be 
abridged.  But the role of the OCR...needs to be narrowed so as to 
allow state and local education officials to develop programs which 
will take into consideration the unique situations of particular 
schools and school districts.  Guidance and assistance, not broad, 
heavy-handed mandates and regulations, should be the role of this 
division.</i>[29]

</blockquote>

<p>

<center><h3>Private Solutions</h3></center>

<p>

The federal lending program for post-secondary education should be 
privatized.  Government should concentrate its limited funds on 
"inherently governmental functions," insists Robert Poole, president 
of the Reason Foundation.   "It should separate policymaking and 
regulation from actual service delivery."[30]

<p>

The federal government entered the educational lending business in 
1972 when it chartered the Student Loan Marketing Association (Sallie 
Mae) to ensure access to student loans for post-secondary education. 
Many argue that Sallie Mae has accomplished that mission and should 
now be privatized.[31] The Clinton Administration appears eager to 
let the quasi-private Sallie Mae do just that so that it may conduct 
a lending program with the exact opposite character: direct lending 
by the federal government.

<p>

Instituted in 1993, the Federal Direct Student Loan Program "has done 
nothing to 'reduce the complexity of administering student loans, 
eliminate unnecessary costs, and provide better service to students 
and schools'" as it claimed it would, according to Allyson Tucker of 
the Heritage Foundation.[32]

<p>

Robert Poole calls privatization "a major worldwide trend,"[33] yet our 
government has chosen to espouse the failed economic philosophy that 
government industries are preferable to private ones.  Bankers are 
doubtful that direct lending will succeed.[34] With the Education 
Department's history of students defaulting on loans, their pessimism 
is not unfounded.  The federal government should get out of the lending 
business; it should also get out of the educational research business.[35]

<p>

The federal government need not be involved for national educational 
research to take place.  Indeed, the most commonly cited measurement 
of student performance -- the Standard Achievement Test (SAT) -- comes 
not from the federal government but from the Educational Testing Service 
(ETS) in Princeton, NJ.

<p>

<center><h3>Conclusion</h3></center>

<p>

Bureaucracies are what bureaucracies do. Goals 2000 and the Elementary 
and Secondary Education Act clearly show the intent of the federal 
Education Department to intrude further into local schools and usurp 
community responsibility. The history standards that the Department 
financed are so biased that the United States Senate renounced them 
in a 99 to 1 vote.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The federal government need<br>
not be involved for national<br>
educational research to take<br>
place.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

If there is one lesson of our times it is that centralization and huge 
bureaucracies don't work very well.  That truth swept away the 
governments of the Soviet Union and half a dozen other countries. 
People in all corners of the globe are moving to take control of their 
own lives back from distant bureaucracies.  Our own nation needs a 
renewal of the local spirit that Alexis de Tocqueville praised so 
highly in 1835:

<p>

<blockquote><i>

I know of no people who have established schools so numerous and 
efficacious, places of public worship better suited to the wants 
of the inhabitants, or roads kept in better repair.  Uniformity 
or permanence of design, the minute arrangement of details, and 
the perfection of administrative system must not be sought for in 
the United States; what we find there is the presence of a power 
which, if it is somewhat wild, is at least robust, and an existence 
checkered with accidents, indeed, but full of animation and effort.</i>[36]

</blockquote>

<p>

It's time to disestablish the U.S. Education Department and end 
the federal intrusion into America's schools.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>- by Jennifer A. Marshall, Education Policy Analyst, and Eric 
Unsworth, Research Fellow</i>.

<p><hr><p>

